WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.800
How do we keep food fresh?

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:19.080
How can we reduce water usage in our daily lives?

00:00:19.080 --> 00:00:24.760
How do we make trash valuable?

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:30.120
How do we innovate to make the world a better place?

00:00:30.120 --> 00:00:40.080
That is what we do.

00:00:40.080 --> 00:00:47.160
So at Dow, we have this graph that measures our net carbon emissions of our entire product

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:48.160
portfolio.

00:00:48.639 --> 00:00:55.840
We've made very ambitious targets related to our carbon neutrality, where by 2050, we

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:58.919
want to reach complete carbon neutrality.

00:00:58.919 --> 00:01:04.599
And with this graph, we can see the various projects, investments, and opportunities we

00:01:04.599 --> 00:01:07.519
have to reduce our carbon footprint.

00:01:07.519 --> 00:01:15.120
And what's also very special about that set of goals is that it's not purely aspirational.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:19.199
We know we have understood the technologies required.

00:01:19.199 --> 00:01:26.400
We have projects in place to account for pretty much 95% of that CO2 mitigation.

00:01:26.400 --> 00:01:34.099
That remaining 5%, it's going to require a lot of creativity and ingenuity from all different

00:01:34.099 --> 00:01:36.199
functions across Dow.

00:01:36.199 --> 00:01:41.320
It's going to be up to us to figure out how to get there.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.120
I work at Dow because I love Dow's mission.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:48.400
We touch Dow products all the time.

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:54.320
They're in food packaging, mattresses, car parts, adhesives.

00:01:54.320 --> 00:01:57.199
And I like to do science to make people's lives better.

00:01:57.199 --> 00:02:01.559
We're also very ambitious because we don't want to just deliver these solutions.

00:02:01.559 --> 00:02:04.320
We want to do it in a sustainable way.

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:10.240
And so all of that involves great technical and technology gaps.

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:15.800
We have a very capable and innovative bunch of researchers that are able to get a lot

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:20.199
done with just about any set of tooling that you throw out of them.

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:28.119
However, the Posit tools, what they've enabled is a extremely low barrier to entry that's

00:02:28.119 --> 00:02:34.880
allowed people who have an idea to go test that idea in a matter of minutes and to be

00:02:34.880 --> 00:02:43.880
able to share the work product of exploring a concept, a Friday afternoon activity, and

00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:48.160
go and share that with some of their colleagues with relative ease.

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:56.080
So I think as scientists, we're very driven towards questioning, questioning the sense

00:02:56.080 --> 00:03:01.479
of making sure that we're doing the right thing or that we should be pursuing the thing

00:03:01.479 --> 00:03:03.559
that we want to pursue.

00:03:03.559 --> 00:03:08.000
It's our critical thinking superpower, and I think it's healthy.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.800
Once we started not only talking about the vision of what these tools could do for us,

00:03:14.800 --> 00:03:20.720
or started building prototypes, a lot of light bulbs started going off in people's head.

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:25.639
Once you have those initial success stories, and then all of these exciting ideas were

00:03:25.639 --> 00:03:33.440
on the table, the conversation was not anymore, why should we do this is how do we do it better?

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:36.320
How do we do it more intentionally?

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:45.639
But there is a moment when it all converges, and it clicks, and it starts flowing.

00:03:45.639 --> 00:03:49.679
And now you have this rhythm.

00:03:49.679 --> 00:03:56.039
Since 2019, we've grown from this handful of researchers to over 300 people now have

00:03:56.039 --> 00:04:01.279
access to Posit Workbench internally, and even more are using apps that are deployed

00:04:01.279 --> 00:04:02.720
on Posit Connect.

00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:08.520
That growth has been, in part, through our investment in Posit Academy, where we're teaching

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:15.720
people how to code using an example and a project that's tailored to the work that we

00:04:15.720 --> 00:04:18.119
expect that they'll use these tools for.

00:04:18.119 --> 00:04:22.000
But also, we've been very intentional about trying to grow this community.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.519
We also have a citizen data science program.

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:28.679
We have more and more people asking us for these capabilities, asking us for these tools

00:04:28.679 --> 00:04:36.880
that they can go use to get more value out of their data, to improve their own productivity.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:46.239
Seeing people who so often may hesitate to put on that I'm a data scientist hat or label,

00:04:46.239 --> 00:04:50.239
but seeing what they're able to create gets me really excited.

00:04:50.239 --> 00:04:54.359
The goal is really to make sure that every person in the organization has some level

00:04:54.359 --> 00:04:59.239
of fluency so they can understand and respect data generated the best possible way.

00:04:59.239 --> 00:05:04.200
When they are showing someone data, they will show with the highest standards of science

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:09.720
and statistics, and that they document properly all the metadata around what they generated

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:14.679
so in the future, people can use them for advanced modeling the best possible way.

00:05:14.679 --> 00:05:22.519
That connection between research and development, between science and doing good, this ability

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:27.920
to use science to make the planet a bit better and to leave it in better conditions for my

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:33.079
kids is extremely important to me.

00:05:33.079 --> 00:05:39.279
In a typical workday, it's easy to get lost in all of those meetings and the busy calendars

00:05:39.279 --> 00:05:41.119
or the kids at home.

00:05:41.119 --> 00:05:46.320
It's easy to get lost in that and forget about the impact that we're going to have.

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:52.040
And it's a huge challenge that we have to face because we're literally taking what previously

00:05:52.040 --> 00:05:56.839
we've looked at as trash and now we want to stick it back into our products.

00:05:56.839 --> 00:06:00.640
Not only is it something we want to do, it's something that we are doing.

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:07.720
When I think about a career at Dow, I want to be able to look back and see the maybe

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:13.440
small but real contribution I will have made to help us reach that, and I think we will.

